  "prompt": "What can I do with an infant at Walt Disney World?",
  "response": "Walt Disney World can be surprisingly fun with an infant! Here's a breakdown of things you can do and tips for making the most of your trip:\n\n**Rides and Attractions:**\n\n*   **Rider Switch/Child Swap:** This is a game-changer! One parent waits in line and rides while the other stays with the baby. After the first parent rides, they switch, and the second parent can ride without waiting in line again. Ask a cast member at the entrance of the ride about using Rider Switch.\n*   **Gentle Rides (Suitable for Infants):** Many rides are slow-moving and gentle, making them perfect for infants. These include:\n    *   **Magic Kingdom:**\n        *   \"it's a small world\"\n        *   Peter Pan's Flight (can be jerky, use caution)\n        *   The Many Adventures of Winnie the Pooh\n        *   Dumbo the Flying Elephant\n        *   Prince Charming Regal Carrousel\n        *   Under the Sea ~ Journey of The Little Mermaid\n        *   Walt Disney World Railroad\n        *   Tomorrowland Transit Authority PeopleMover\n        *   Jungle Cruise (can be loud)\n        *   Liberty Square Riverboat\n        *   Buzz Lightyear's Space Ranger Spin (infant might need to be held securely)\n    *   **Epcot:**\n        *   Spaceship Earth\n        *   Gran Fiesta Tour Starring The Three Caballeros (Mexico Pavilion)\n        *   Living with the Land (The Land Pavilion)\n        *   Journey into Imagination with Figment\n        *   The Seas with Nemo & Friends\n    *   **Hollywood Studios:**\n        *   Toy Story Mania! (Hold the baby securely - it can be jerky)\n        *   Mickey & Minnie's Runaway Railway\n    *   **Animal Kingdom:**\n        *   Kilimanjaro Safaris (can be bumpy, hold baby securely)\n        *   Na'vi River Journey\n        *   TriceraTop Spin\n        *   Wildlife Express Train\n*   **Consider Skip the Line Options:**\n    *   **Genie+:** Paid service that allows you to book ride reservations one at a time throughout the day, significantly reducing wait times for eligible attractions.\n    *   **Individual Lightning Lane Selections:**  These are for the most popular rides, and you pay a separate fee per ride, per person.\n*   **Check Height Restrictions:** While many rides are suitable for infants, always double-check height restrictions if you're unsure.\n\n**Other Activities:**\n\n*   **Shows and Parades:** Many shows and parades are captivating for babies, even if they don't fully understand what's happening. Find a good viewing spot where you can comfortably stand or sit with the baby.\n*   **Character Meet-and-Greets:**  Babies often react adorably to characters. Take advantage of these photo opportunities!\n*   **Play Areas:** Most parks have dedicated play areas where your baby can stretch their legs and interact with other children.\n*   **Aquarium Viewing:** The Seas with Nemo & Friends pavilion at Epcot offers a large aquarium that can be mesmerizing for babies.\n*   **Walking and Exploring:** Simply strolling around the parks and taking in the sights and sounds can be enjoyable for both you and your baby.\n\n**Baby Care Centers:**\n\n*   These centers are a lifesaver! Each park has a dedicated Baby Care Center offering:\n    *   Private nursing rooms with rocking chairs\n    *   Changing tables\n    *   Quiet areas for feeding\n    *   Microwaves for warming bottles and food\n    *   High chairs\n    *   A shop selling diapers, wipes, formula, and other baby necessities\n\n**Tips for Traveling with an Infant at Disney World:**\n\n*   **Plan for Breaks:** Don't try to cram too much into each day. Schedule regular breaks for naps, feedings, and quiet time.\n*   **Bring a Stroller or Baby Carrier:** A stroller or carrier is essential for navigating the parks. Disney allows strollers, but there are size restrictions (31\" wide x 52\" long).  A lightweight, foldable stroller is ideal. Baby carriers (like Ergobaby, Lillebaby, or wraps) are also great for navigating crowds and attractions.\n*   **Stay Hydrated and Cool:** Florida weather can be hot and humid. Ensure your baby stays hydrated and cool. Dress them in lightweight, breathable clothing, use sunscreen, and provide shade with a stroller canopy or hat.\n*   **Pack Smart:**\n    *   Plenty of diapers and wipes\n    *   Formula or breast milk (if applicable)\n    *   Bottles or sippy cups\n    *   Baby food or snacks\n    *   Sunscreen\n    *   Hats\n    *   Lightweight blankets\n    *   Change of clothes (or two!)\n    *   Toys and books\n    *   Any necessary medications\n*   **Take Advantage of Mobile Ordering:** Use the My Disney Experience app to order food in advance and skip the lines at quick-service restaurants.\n*   **Consider a Resort with Good Transportation:** Choose a resort with easy access to the parks via monorail, boat, or bus.\n*   **Talk to Cast Members:** Disney Cast Members are incredibly helpful and can offer advice, assistance, and information.\n*   **Adjust Your Expectations:**  Traveling with an infant is different from traveling without one. Be prepared to be flexible and adjust your plans as needed. Focus on making memories and enjoying the experience together.\n*   **Consider a Rest Day:**  Spending a day at the resort pool can be a welcome break for everyone.\n*   **Disney's Baby Amenities:**  You can often find high chairs at quick service dining locations.  Many restrooms also have changing tables.\n*   **Renting Equipment:** Consider renting a stroller or crib from a local company like Kingdom Strollers or Magic Strollers.  This can be more convenient than bringing your own.\n\n**Important Considerations:**\n\n*   **Sun Protection:**  Florida sun is strong. Use sunscreen (baby-safe formula), hats, and protective clothing.\n*   **Crowds:** Disney World can be very crowded, especially during peak seasons. Be prepared for crowds and long wait times.\n*   **Noise:** The parks can be noisy, which may overwhelm some babies. Consider bringing noise-canceling headphones or earplugs.\n*   **Vaccinations:** Ensure your baby is up-to-date on all vaccinations before traveling.\n\nWith careful planning and preparation, you can have a magical Walt Disney World vacation with your infant!  Remember to prioritize your baby's comfort and needs, and focus on creating special memories. Good luck!\n",
